  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skimping on Insurance</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Indonesia's healthcare outside Jakarta is limited. Bali's hospitals handle basics but not complex cases. Singapore evacuation can cost $30,000+ without insurance. Don't use cheap local insurance as your only coverage—it could be a life-threatening mistake.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming Work Rights</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Second Home Visa explicitly prohibits working in Indonesia. Remote work for overseas employers is tolerated in practice but not officially authorized. If you need to work for Indonesian clients or companies, you need different visa (KITAS with work permit).</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Forgetting Exit Requirement</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Second Home Visa is multiple entry but requires you to exit and re-enter at least once per year to keep it valid. Many people do Singapore or Malaysia trips. Mark your calendar—overstaying or not exiting can cause visa issues.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting Property Ownership</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Foreigners cannot own freehold land in Indonesia. You can lease (hak pakai) for up to 80 years or own apartments in certain buildings. Many "ownership" structures involve Indonesian nominees—risky. Understand property law before buying.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Bali Traffic/Crowds</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Bali's popular areas (Canggu, Seminyak) have serious traffic and overtourism. Dry season is crowded. Consider Ubud, Sanur, or less developed areas for better quality of life. Bali isn't all rice paddies and empty beaches anymore.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

