  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I become an Indonesian citizen?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Generally no. Indonesia doesn't allow naturalization except in very rare circumstances (long-term marriage to Indonesian citizen, exceptional contribution to Indonesia). Plan for long-term residence, not citizenship. Second Home Visa gives you up to 10 years—renew or adjust plans after.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I buy property in Indonesia?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Foreigners cannot own freehold land (hak milik). Options include: Right to Use (hak pakai) up to 80 years for land, apartment ownership (strata title) in certain buildings, or leasehold arrangements. Many villa "purchases" are actually long-term leases. Consult Indonesian property lawyer before buying.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work remotely on Second Home Visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Officially, Second Home Visa doesn't include work authorization. Practically, remote work for overseas employers is widely practiced and tolerated. You cannot work for Indonesian companies or Indonesian clients. Keep a low profile and don't advertise working—it's a gray area.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the difference between Second Home and Retirement KITAS?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Second Home Visa: Any age, $130K savings + $1,400/month income, 5-10 years, no sponsor needed. Retirement KITAS: Age 55+, $1,500/month pension, 1 year renewable (max 5 years), requires Indonesian sponsor. Second Home is more flexible; Retirement KITAS is for those who don't meet savings requirement but have pension.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Bali safe for families?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, Bali is generally safe and welcoming for families. International schools (Green School, Canggu Community School) are popular. Healthcare is adequate for routine pediatrics; serious issues go to Singapore. Traffic and motorbike culture are risks—many families live in quieter areas like Ubud or Sanur rather than busy Canggu.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does the $130K savings requirement work?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          You must show bank statements proving $130,000 in savings/liquid assets. The money doesn't need to be invested in Indonesia or held there—just proven to exist in your accounts. You should maintain this level for visa renewals. It's proof of financial capacity, not an investment requirement.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

